The basic historical situation is that there were=C2=A0commercial banks=C2=
=A0and=C2=A0investment banks.
  [1]
=C2=A0Commercial banks did things like lending money to companies, making m=
ortgage loans, offering checking accounts and issuing credit cards. Investm=
ent banks traded stocks and bonds and offered advice to companies on merger=
s and stock and bond offerings. In the US, the Glass-Steagall Act of 1933=
=C2=A0kept these businesses separate, more or less prohibiting commercial b=
anks from trading stocks and bonds, and investment banks from taking deposi=
ts.=C2=A0
Like any big company, these companies had different divisions, different bu=
siness lines. A commercial bank=C2=A0might have a division that loaned mone=
y to companies, and another that did transaction banking (checking accounts=
, etc.) for companies, and one that did mortgages, and one that did credit =
cards. An investment bank, confusingly, would have an =E2=80=9Cinvestment b=
anking division=E2=80=9D that advised companies on mergers and stock and bo=
nd offerings, and a division (=E2=80=9Csales and trading=E2=80=9D or perhap=
s =E2=80=9Csecurities=E2=80=9D) that traded stocks and bonds for clients. A=
nd there was some overlap; both investment banks and commercial banks were =
often=C2=A0in the business of managing money for clients, and so they might=
 each have an asset management or wealth management division.
Over time, as markets and regulations changed, this separation got weaker, =
and by the early 21st century in the US banks could be in both businesses. =
There were obvious advantages: If=C2=A0a company wants to buy another compa=
ny and needs to borrow money to do it, and you are advising them on the mer=
ger, and they say =E2=80=9Cwhere will we borrow this money,=E2=80=9D and yo=
u say =E2=80=9Chere=E2=80=99s a list of good banks you can borrow from,=E2=
=80=9D that is helpful, but it is much more helpful for them (and much more=
 profitable for you) if you can say =E2=80=9Cyou can borrow it from us, her=
e it is.=E2=80=9D
Also, if you are in the business of trading=C2=A0stocks and bonds, you will=
 want a lot of leverage: You are making small amounts of money trading huge=
 amounts of securities, so you will want to do it mostly with borrowed mone=
y. There is a broad intuitive belief that it is=C2=A0cheaper=C2=A0for a big=
 commercial bank to borrow money than it is for a big investment bank. If a=
 big investment bank wants to borrow money, it has to go to other banks or =
institutional investors and say =E2=80=9Chey I=E2=80=99d like to borrow mon=
ey to trade stocks and bonds, but don=E2=80=99t worry, I=E2=80=99ll do it v=
ery safely,=E2=80=9D and that will basically work but the lenders will char=
ge for it. If a big commercial bank wants to borrow money, it opens some br=
anches and people come in and open government-insured=C2=A0checking account=
s that pay 0% interest, and the bank gets to use that money.
This is oversimplified in various ways, and it is not actually obvious that=
 =E2=80=9Clet=E2=80=99s get retail deposits and use them to run a trading b=
usiness" is a viable or even desirable plan. But there is a subtler advanta=
ge, which is that commercial banks are=C2=A0banks, and when they=C2=A0run i=
nto liquidity trouble they can borrow money from the Federal Reserve, while=
 investment banks are not, strictly speaking, banks, and=C2=A0can=E2=80=99t=
. If you are in the business of trading securities with lots of borrowed mo=
ney, and then markets get scary and people stop lending you money, you go b=
ankrupt. You can call your lenders and say =E2=80=9Cno, see, we have all th=
ese securities that are still good, you should still lend us the money,=E2=
=80=9D but if they=E2=80=99re spooked they just won=E2=80=99t answer the ph=
one.=C2=A0But if you can call the Fed it will answer the phone, and if the =
securities are still good it will lend you the money. It is good, in a very=
 leveraged business, to have access to a lender of last resort.
And so big commercial banks started building or acquiring investment banks,=
 and=C2=A0by the time I started in investment banking in the middle of the =
last decade, there were three sorts of places you could be an investment ba=
nker:
=09Universal banks like JPMorgan Chase & Co. or Citigroup, which were big c=
ommercial banks with investment banks inside of them;=09Investment banking =
boutiques, which were smaller investment banks that had only an investment =
banking division, so they advised clients on mergers but mostly did not tra=
de stocks and bonds (or need to borrow lots of money); and=09=E2=80=9CFull-=
service investment banks=E2=80=9D like Goldman Sachs Group Inc. (where I wo=
rked), Morgan Stanley, Merrill Lynch, Lehman Brothers and Bear Stearns.

And then the 2008 financial crisis hit and the independent full-service inv=
estment banking model ended.
  [2]
=C2=A0It turned out to be too risky to run a giant institutional sales and =
trading business without a lender of last resort.=C2=A0Merrill and Bear got=
 bought by universal banks (Bank of America, JPMorgan). Lehman went bankrup=
t and got sold off in parts to=C2=A0universal banks (Nomura, Barclays).
Goldman and Morgan Stanley did something different, though; they=C2=A0becam=
e=C2=A0universal banks. In September 2008, they  converted into commercial =
banks in order to get access to the Fed. And then they came into work the n=
ext day and, uh, survived. They did not convert into commercial banks with =
ambitious plans to get into corporate lending and retail banking, to issue =
credit cards and mortgages. They converted into commercial banks over a sca=
ry weekend in order to keep access to funding for their trading businesses.=
=C2=A0They were=C2=A0technically=C2=A0universal banks, but=C2=A0really=C2=
=A0they remained independent full-service investment banks.
But eventually, as things stabilized, they thought, well, we=C2=A0have=C2=
=A0this commercial banking license, we might as well=C2=A0use=C2=A0it. Gold=
man, in particular, launched online savings accounts for retail customers, =
with a new brand (Marcus) for its retail business.=C2=A0It got into the cre=
dit card business. It did commercial-banking type things. These things were=
 =E2=80=A6=C2=A0cute? The tone of reporting on them was often =E2=80=9Caww =
how sweet, Goldman is doing consumer banking.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
There is one historical organizational=C2=A0difference between an investmen=
t-bank-that-accidentally-became-a-universal-bank and a real universal bank.=
 A real universal bank has=C2=A0a number of divisions =E2=80=94=C2=A0corpor=
ate lending, consumer banking, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0and one of them is =E2=
=80=9Cthe investment bank,=E2=80=9D housing investment banking and sales an=
d trading and research. If you run=C2=A0sales and trading at a universal ba=
nk, you generally report to the head of the investment bank, who reports to=
 the chief executive officer of the whole company. An investment bank=C2=A0=
is=C2=A0the investment bank. It might have a division for consumer lending,=
 now, but its top-level divisions will include =E2=80=9Cinvestment banking=
=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Csales and trading.=E2=80=9D If you run sales and tra=
ding at a freestanding investment bank, you report to the CEO. Because cult=
urally that CEO is the CEO of the investment bank, because culturally the w=
hole company is the investment bank.
Goldman is   now a universal bank I guess:

Goldman Sachs Group Inc=E2=80=99s David Solomon is embarking on his third m=
ajor reorganization in just four years as chief executive officer, undoing =
some of the signature moves he made as recently as 2020.
The Wall Street giant plans to once again combine its expanded asset manage=
ment and private wealth businesses into one unit run by Marc Nachmann, acco=
rding to people familiar with the matter. Goldman will also fuse its invest=
ment-banking and trading operations under one group run by Dan Dees, Jim Es=
posito and Ashok Varadhan. The money-losing consumer unit will be broken up=
. =E2=80=A6
A smaller subset of the consumer-banking business that deals with corporate=
 partners will emerge as a standalone entity called Platform Solutions run =
by Stephanie Cohen, the people said, asking not to be identified discussing=
 information that=E2=80=99s not yet public.
That includes GreenSky, the installment-lending firm it bought last year, a=
long with its credit-card ventures and transaction banking, which handles c=
orporate deposits and was previously part of the investment-banking group.=
=C2=A0

So Goldman will have  three divisions, roughly transaction banking, money m=
anagement, and the investment bank. I don=E2=80=99t know how much that matt=
ers:
The changes to the banking and trading business are expected to be minimal,=
 with the remaining slate of leaders taking over the reins of the new, comb=
ined group. The combination is driven partly by a shift to showcase to inve=
stors the relative strength of that business compared with peers across Wal=
l Street.
But it seems culturally significant. For its entire history until this week=
, Goldman=C2=A0was=C2=A0an investment bank. Now it is=C2=A0a big financial =
company that=C2=A0has=C2=A0an investment bank.

