   =20
      Anti-ESG
   =20
 =20

If a municipality puts a bond financing out for competitive bids, and the w=
inning bidder is a bank that sometimes considers environmental, social and =
governance factors in some of its investing and financing decisions, and th=
en the municipality decides to boycott banks that consider ESG factors, and=
 so it cancels the financing with the winning bank, and instead does a wors=
e financing with another bank that never considers ESG factors, and as a re=
sult it has to pay more money for financing, whose fault is that? I mean =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0there is an obvious answer? It=E2=80=99s the municipality=E2=
=80=99s fault? I do not see how you could say it=E2=80=99s the=C2=A0bank=E2=
=80=99s=C2=A0fault?=C2=A0But you can try I guess?

Weeks after a Texas school district dropped UBS Group AG as its municipal-b=
ond underwriter because state Republicans labeled it unfriendly to the oil =
industry, it=E2=80=99s now demanding the bank cover the costs of having to =
redo the sale.
The Normangee Independent School District was forced to redo an $18 million=
 bond sale that had already been underwritten by UBS Financial Services aft=
er the bank=E2=80=99s parent company in August was added to a list of firms=
 that the GOP state comptroller considers to =E2=80=9Cboycott=E2=80=9D the =
fossil fuels industry. =C2=A0
The district is demanding UBS refund it for the costs it incurred after it =
had to resell the debt as a result. Municipal-bond yields surged dramatical=
ly and made it more expensive to reissue the debt. But the school district =
blames UBS -- not the Republican attorney general=E2=80=99s office that is =
enforcing the law. In fact, the attorney general=E2=80=99s office is repres=
enting the district in its effort to recoup the costs incurred from having =
to resell the debt, according to a document provided through a public recor=
ds request.
=E2=80=9CNISD resold the bonds and hired a different underwriter, at a loss=
 to NISD,=E2=80=9D Lauren Downey, assistant attorney general and public inf=
ormation coordinator, said in the Oct. 12 dated document. =E2=80=9CIn the e=
vent the OAG is unable to successfully negotiate a resolution with UBS, our=
 office anticipates filing suit.=E2=80=9D

We  talked on Thursday about two somewhat contradictory visions of anti-ESG=
:
=09One vision is that states=C2=A0should reject ESG and try only=C2=A0to ma=
ximize their financial returns, without worrying about social or political =
factors.=09The other vision is that Republican-run states should reject ESG=
 because =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D tends to involve left-wing priorities, and R=
epublican-run states should instead pursue right-wing priorities with their=
 investments.

Most people=C2=A0in the anti-ESG movement will=C2=A0tell=C2=A0you that it i=
s just about maximizing financial returns and avoiding politics. But then y=
ou get a case like this where the school district simply incinerates some m=
oney to pursue=C2=A0Republican political goals! But they had the nerve to a=
sk the bank for the money back.

