   =20
      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20

Meanwhile Elon Musk has about $7 billion of equity commitments from his fri=
ends, crypto exchanges, Middle Eastern funds, etc., to join his deal to buy=
 Twitter, and there is some uncertainty about whether those people will act=
ually kick in the money or whether Musk will have to cover their checks. My=
  rough assumption is that (1) those people probably=C2=A0could=C2=A0get ou=
t of their commitments, since Musk terminated the deal three times, so it=
=E2=80=99s a little tough for him to argue that it=E2=80=99s still binding =
on them, but (2) they probably=C2=A0won=E2=80=99t, because they signed up f=
or the deal based mostly on blind faith in (or desire to be close to) Musk,=
 and nothing about that rationale has really changed. Here is a counterargu=
ment though:

"We're all trying to get out of it, to be honest," said Andrea Walne, a gen=
eral partner at Manhattan Venture Partners.
MVP committed to invest in the deal earlier this year, but a question remai=
ns as to whether the firm and others will actually be on the hook for the f=
ull amount they committed to, according to Walne. "We talked to the other i=
nvestors, everyone's trying to get out of it, no one thinks the company sho=
uld be valued at $44 billion," she said.
Citing the sharp downturn in equity markets over the last 6 months, Walne s=
aid she would put the value of Twitter at this point closer to $10 billion =
to $12 billion, a far cry from the $44 billion that Musk has agreed to pay.

Look selfishly I am hoping that some of them back out and he sues them, arg=
uing that in fact the deal was never terminated and Twitter is still worth =
$44 billion. That would be a great continuation to this story. But, no, my =
assumption is that most of them won=E2=80=99t back out (to avoid offending =
Musk), but if they do he won=E2=80=99t sue them (because it=E2=80=99s not w=
orth it). But I confess that I don=E2=80=99t understand=C2=A0this=C2=A0stra=
tegy. If you go around=C2=A0telling journalists on the record=C2=A0that you=
=E2=80=99re trying to get out of it, then you are offending Musk! But you m=
ight still send in the money, for a deal you hate! The move is to say nothi=
ng and=C2=A0not=C2=A0send in the money.
Elsewhere, the Information reports that =E2=80=9CMusk Will Have Absolute Co=
ntrol Over Twitter, Documents Show=E2=80=9D:

Elon Musk may be relying on outside investors to help finance his $44 billi=
on purchase of Twitter. But that doesn=E2=80=99t mean he=E2=80=99s giving t=
hose investors a say in how the company is run.
A shareholders=E2=80=99 agreement prepared by Musk=E2=80=99s lawyers for eq=
uity investors shows that Musk will retain absolute authority over key deci=
sions. He will have =E2=80=9Csole discretion=E2=80=9D to decide whether to =
pursue a sale of the company, an initial public offering or some other refi=
nancing transaction involving the business, for instance.=C2=A0

Yeah I can=E2=80=99t imagine doing it any other way. He=E2=80=99s putting i=
n the majority of the equity check, it was his idea, and he=E2=80=99s Elon =
Musk. Nobody signed up for this deal planning to=C2=A0supervise=C2=A0how Mu=
sk runs Twitter.
And Matt Yglesias notes that Musk=E2=80=99s ties to China (in his role as t=
he head of Tesla Inc.) might make it hard for him to run Twitter on =E2=80=
=9Cfree speech=E2=80=9D lines:
Does this mean that a Musk-run Twitter is going to impose China-friendly ce=
nsorship as heavy-handed as the self-censorship Musk practices in his perso=
nal commentary? That he=E2=80=99s going to turn it into a China-free zone t=
he way that Apple has with its content business?
=E2=80=9CProbably not,=E2=80=9D he answers, but the worry seems fair:
What does Twitter do once it=E2=80=99s owned by the CEO of a major industri=
al brand? I don=E2=80=99t know, but I wish the reporters on the Musk beat w=
ould ask. And frankly, I wish Congress and the FTC would, too.
The problem is, what do you do about it?
  [3]
=C2=A0You could imagine a world in which the US government had some sort of=
 regulatory apparatus for social media companies that:
=09Had some rules about how they treat content;=C2=A0=09Had a regulatory ag=
ency that wrote and enforced those rules;=09Had pre-merger review that coul=
d approve or reject acquisitions based on the suitability of a new owner, o=
r could extract conditions (=E2=80=9CYou can run Twitter, but you can=E2=80=
=99t censor content on behalf of China=E2=80=9D) for approving an acquisiti=
on.

There are regimes sort of like that for other industries =E2=80=94=C2=A0if =
you want to buy a casino, gaming regulators will take a hard look at your p=
ersonal qualifications =E2=80=94=C2=A0but social media rose to prominence i=
n a deregulatory age, plus, can you imagine how this system would actually=
=C2=A0work? (Would the Federal Social Media Agency require Twitter to ban a=
nti-Semitic tweets, or require it to allow them?) And so in practice Musk=
=E2=80=99s acquisition of Twitter got reviewed mainly for antitrust concern=
s, and there were none, so it was quickly approved. I  wrote back in April:
It is not in a heavily regulated industry, and there=E2=80=99s no particula=
r antitrust problem with Musk acquiring it. =E2=80=9CWorld=E2=80=99s riches=
t person acquires the main venue for public communication=E2=80=9D does see=
m like the sort of thing that ought to raise regulatory concerns, but in ou=
r actually existing system I=E2=80=99m not sure what those concerns would b=
e.=C2=A0
I mean, I can see the=C2=A0concerns=C2=A0that it raises, but not the=C2=A0r=
egulatory=C2=A0concerns.

