   =20
      SPACs
   =20
 =20

I feel like people do not understand the basic economic proposition=C2=A0of=
 a special purpose acquisition company?   A SPAC is a gamble by its sponsor=
s. The sponsors put in some money =E2=80=94=C2=A0let=E2=80=99s say it=E2=80=
=99s $8 million =E2=80=94=C2=A0to pay startup costs to raise a pool of cash=
 from public investors. Then they have about two years to look for a privat=
e company to merge with and take public. If they find a target, negotiate a=
 merger, get approval from the public investors, and take it public, then t=
hey make a lot of money. Let=E2=80=99s say they make $54 million, or roughl=
y seven times what they put in. Good payoff. If they fail to find a target,=
 or they can=E2=80=99t negotiate the deal, or if the public investors don=
=E2=80=99t approve of the deal, then they lose their $8 million.
Meanwhile the public investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0the people who put money into=
 the pool of cash =E2=80=94=C2=A0get back (1) shares of the target company,=
 if the SPAC succeeds, or (2) the money they put in, with a little bit of i=
nterest, if it fails. In Case 2, the public investors basically break even;=
 the interest they got from the=C2=A0SPAC isn=E2=80=99t materially worse th=
an they would have gotten in a bank account. In Case 1, the public investor=
s get shares in a newly public company, which is good if the company is goo=
d or bad if the company is bad. So you could separate the public investors=
=E2=80=99 result into Case 1a, =E2=80=9Cshares that go up,=E2=80=9D and Cas=
e 1b, =E2=80=9Cshares that go down.=E2=80=9D In Case 1a, you=E2=80=99re hap=
py; getting valuable shares is better than getting your money back. In Case=
 1b, you=E2=80=99re sad, and you would rather have gotten your money back.
But all that stuff is virtually irrelevant for the SPAC=E2=80=99s=C2=A0spon=
sors. The sponsors lose $8 million in Case 2: The public investors break ev=
en, but the sponsors lose their investment. And the sponsors get $54 millio=
n in Case 1 =E2=80=94=C2=A01a or 1b, doesn=E2=80=99t matter =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
because for=C2=A0them, all that matters is doing the deal. If they do a dea=
l, they get $54 million; if they don=E2=80=99t, they lose $8 million.
This is not=C2=A0quite=C2=A0right; there are features that align the intere=
sts of the SPAC=E2=80=99s sponsors with the public investors more than what=
 I have suggested here. The big one is that the sponsors do not literally g=
et a check for $54 million: They get (roughly $54 million worth of) shares =
in the target company, and the more valuable that ends up being the better =
they do. (There are also various sorts of lockups, clawbacks, etc., to make=
 the sponsors=E2=80=99 success more contingent on the company=E2=80=99s suc=
cess. Also, the public investors get to vote on the deal, and presumably th=
ey=E2=80=99ll vote no on bad deals.) But even if the target company does=C2=
=A0terribly, the sponsors get so many shares that they make a huge profit,=
=C2=A0as long as they actually do the deal.=C2=A0
Anyway here=E2=80=99s  a Wall Street Journal article:

As the air has come out of the SPAC boom of recent years, a clear winner ha=
s emerged: the money managers who oversaw the blank-check companies and who=
 kept making profits even in the face of significant losses to stock invest=
ors.=C2=A0
Stock-market investors in SPACs that merged with private companies since 20=
15 lost an average 37% of their investment a year after the merger through =
the end of September, according to the authors of a forthcoming paper on SP=
ACs in the Review of Financial Studies, an academic journal.=C2=A0
At the same time, SPAC managers, known as sponsors, turned an average inves=
tment of about $8 million into about $54 million, giving them average annua=
lized returns of 110% on their initial investment in the SPACs, the authors=
 found.=C2=A0

Yes look this is right as far as it goes, but it looks only at a subset of =
SPACs, the subset of =E2=80=9CSPACs that merged with private companies.=E2=
=80=9D That=E2=80=99s like saying that people who bought winning lottery ti=
ckets, on average, made money. If you ran a SPAC that succeeded =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0by the narrow SPAC standard of =E2=80=9Cdid a merger=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0then you turned $8 million into $54 million, even though the publi=
c investors lost money. But if you ran a SPAC that failed =E2=80=94=C2=A0th=
at didn=E2=80=99t find a merger =E2=80=94=C2=A0then you turned $8 million i=
nto zero, while your public investors got their money back with interest.
Obviously the point here is that success for the public investors is the op=
posite: You=E2=80=99d rather get your money back than lose 37% of your inve=
stment. On average, sponsors do better from the SPACs that succeed, but reg=
ular investors do better from the ones that fail.

