10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Goldman</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic historical situation is that there w=
ere=C2=A0<em>commercial banks=C2=A0</em>and=C2=A0<em>investment banks</em>.=
<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: trans=
parent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Commercial banks did things like lending money to companies, maki=
ng mortgage loans, offering checking accounts and issuing credit cards. Inv=
estment banks traded stocks and bonds and offered advice to companies on me=
rgers and stock and bond offerings. In the US, the <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29401395.284514/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaW=
Eub3JnL3dpa2kvR2xhc3MlRTIlODAlOTNTdGVhZ2FsbF9sZWdpc2xhdGlvbg/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cB842b2600" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">Glass-Steagall Act of 1933</a>=C2=A0kept thes=
e businesses separate, more or less prohibiting commercial banks from tradi=
ng stocks and bonds, and investment banks from taking deposits.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Like any big company, these companies had diff=
erent divisions, different business lines. A commercial bank=C2=A0might hav=
e a division that loaned money to companies, and another that did transacti=
on banking (checking accounts, etc.) for companies, and one that did mortga=
ges, and one that did credit cards. An investment bank, confusingly, would =
have an =E2=80=9Cinvestment banking division=E2=80=9D that advised companie=
s on mergers and stock and bond offerings, and a division (=E2=80=9Csales a=
nd trading=E2=80=9D or perhaps =E2=80=9Csecurities=E2=80=9D) that traded st=
ocks and bonds for clients. And there was some overlap; both investment ban=
ks and commercial banks were often=C2=A0in the business of managing money f=
or clients, and so they might each have an asset management or wealth manag=
ement division.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Over time, as markets and regulations changed,=
 this separation got weaker, and by the early 21st century in the US banks =
could be in both businesses. There were obvious advantages: If=C2=A0a compa=
ny wants to buy another company and needs to borrow money to do it, and you=
 are advising them on the merger, and they say =E2=80=9Cwhere will we borro=
w this money,=E2=80=9D and you say =E2=80=9Chere=E2=80=99s a list of good b=
anks you can borrow from,=E2=80=9D that is helpful, but it is much more hel=
pful for them (and much more profitable for you) if you can say =E2=80=9Cyo=
u can borrow it from us, here it is.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, if you are in the business of trading=C2=
=A0stocks and bonds, you will want a lot of leverage: You are making small =
amounts of money trading huge amounts of securities, so you will want to do=
 it mostly with borrowed money. There is a broad intuitive belief that it i=
s=C2=A0<em>cheaper=C2=A0</em>for a big commercial bank to borrow money than=
 it is for a big investment bank. If a big investment bank wants to borrow =
money, it has to go to other banks or institutional investors and say =E2=
=80=9Chey I=E2=80=99d like to borrow money to trade stocks and bonds, but d=
on=E2=80=99t worry, I=E2=80=99ll do it very safely,=E2=80=9D and that will =
basically work but the lenders will charge for it. If a big commercial bank=
 wants to borrow money, it opens some branches and people come in and open =
government-insured=C2=A0checking accounts that pay 0% interest, and the ban=
k gets to use that money.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is oversimplified in various ways, and it=
 is not actually obvious that =E2=80=9Clet=E2=80=99s get retail deposits an=
d use them to run a trading business" is a viable or even desirable plan. B=
ut there is a subtler advantage, which is that commercial banks are=C2=A0<e=
m>banks</em>, and when they=C2=A0run into liquidity trouble they can borrow=
 money from the Federal Reserve, while investment banks are not, strictly s=
peaking, banks, and=C2=A0can=E2=80=99t. If you are in the business of tradi=
ng securities with lots of borrowed money, and then markets get scary and p=
eople stop lending you money, you go bankrupt. You can call your lenders an=
d say =E2=80=9Cno, see, we have all these securities that are still good, y=
ou should still lend us the money,=E2=80=9D but if they=E2=80=99re spooked =
they just won=E2=80=99t answer the phone.=C2=A0But if you can call the Fed =
it will answer the phone, and if the securities are still good it will lend=
 you the money. It is good, in a very leveraged business, to have access to=
 a lender of last resort.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so big commercial banks started building o=
r acquiring investment banks, and=C2=A0by the time I started in investment =
banking in the middle of the last decade, there were three sorts of places =
you could be an investment banker:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Universal banks like JPMorgan Chase &a=
mp; Co. or Citigroup, which were big commercial banks with investment banks=
 inside of them;</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Investment bankin=
g boutiques, which were smaller investment banks that had only an investmen=
t banking division, so they advised clients on mergers but mostly did not t=
rade stocks and bonds (or need to borrow lots of money); and</li>=09<li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=E2=80=9CFull-service investment banks=E2=80=9D =
like Goldman Sachs Group Inc. (where I worked), Morgan Stanley, Merrill Lyn=
ch, Lehman Brothers and Bear Stearns.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then the 2008 financial crisis hit and the=
 independent full-service investment banking model ended.<a class=3D"footno=
te-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: no=
ne !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bord=
er-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important;=
 display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0It turned out to be too risky to run a giant institutional sales =
and trading business without a lender of last resort.=C2=A0Merrill and Bear=
 got bought by universal banks (Bank of America, JPMorgan). Lehman went ban=
krupt and got sold off in parts to=C2=A0universal banks (Nomura, Barclays).=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Goldman and Morgan Stanley did something diffe=
rent, though; they=C2=A0<em>became=C2=A0</em>universal banks. In September =
2008, they <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2940139=
5.284514/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29sZG1hbnNhY2hzLmNvbS9vdXItZmlybS9oaXN0b3J5L21vbW=
VudHMvMjAwOC1iYW5rLWhvbGRpbmctY29tcGFueS5odG1sIzp-OnRleHQ9R29sZG1hbiUyMFNhY=
2hzJTIwQW5ub3VuY2VzJTIwSXQlMjBXaWxsJTIwQmVjb21lJTIwYSUyMEJhbmslMjBIb2xkaW5n=
JTIwQ29tcGFueSwtVGhlbWUlM0ElMjBDbGllbnRzJnRleHQ9SW4lMjBTZXB0ZW1iZXIlMjAyMDA=
4JTJDJTIwZGF5cyUyMGFmdGVyLGNhcGl0YWwlMkMlMjBsaXF1aWRpdHklMjBhbmQlMjBjb21wZX=
RpdGl2ZSUyMHBvc2l0aW9uLg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd5dfffbc" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> conver=
ted into commercial banks</a> in order to get access to the Fed. And then t=
hey came into work the next day and, uh, survived. They did not convert int=
o commercial banks with ambitious plans to get into corporate lending and r=
etail banking, to issue credit cards and mortgages. They converted into com=
mercial banks over a scary weekend in order to keep access to funding for t=
heir trading businesses.=C2=A0They were=C2=A0<em>technically=C2=A0</em>univ=
ersal banks, but=C2=A0<em>really=C2=A0</em>they remained independent full-s=
ervice investment banks.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But eventually, as things stabilized, they tho=
ught, well, we=C2=A0<em>have=C2=A0</em>this commercial banking license, we =
might as well=C2=A0<em>use=C2=A0</em>it. Goldman, in particular, launched o=
nline savings accounts for retail customers, with a new brand (Marcus) for =
its retail business.=C2=A0It got into the credit card business. It did comm=
ercial-banking type things. These things were =E2=80=A6=C2=A0cute? The tone=
 of reporting on them was often =E2=80=9Caww how sweet, Goldman is doing co=
nsumer banking.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is one historical organizational=C2=A0di=
fference between an investment-bank-that-accidentally-became-a-universal-ba=
nk and a real universal bank. A real universal bank has=C2=A0a number of di=
visions =E2=80=94=C2=A0corporate lending, consumer banking, etc. =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0and one of them is =E2=80=9Cthe investment bank,=E2=80=9D housing inv=
estment banking and sales and trading and research. If you run=C2=A0sales a=
nd trading at a universal bank, you generally report to the head of the inv=
estment bank, who reports to the chief executive officer of the whole compa=
ny. An investment bank=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>the investment bank. It might =
have a division for consumer lending, now, but its top-level divisions will=
 include =E2=80=9Cinvestment banking=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Csales and tradin=
g.=E2=80=9D If you run sales and trading at a freestanding investment bank,=
 you report to the CEO. Because culturally that CEO is the CEO of the inves=
tment bank, because culturally the whole company is the investment bank.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Goldman is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/29401395.284514/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZ=
XdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTAtMTcvZ29sZG1hbi1jZW8tc2hha2VzLXVwLWxlYWRlcnNoaXAt=
cmFua3MtaW4teWV0LWFub3RoZXItb3ZlcmhhdWw_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTAxNzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkY=
mdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMDE3Jn=
V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe8cea516" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  now a universal bank I guess</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Goldman Sachs Group Inc=E2=80=99s David Solomo=
n is embarking on his third major reorganization in just four years as chie=
f executive officer, undoing some of the signature moves he made as recentl=
y as 2020.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Wall Street giant plans to once again comb=
ine its expanded asset management and private wealth businesses into one un=
it run by Marc Nachmann, according to people familiar with the matter. Gold=
man will also fuse its investment-banking and trading operations under one =
group run by Dan Dees, Jim Esposito and Ashok Varadhan. The money-losing co=
nsumer unit will be broken up. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A smaller subset of the consumer-banking busin=
ess that deals with corporate partners will emerge as a standalone entity c=
alled Platform Solutions run by Stephanie Cohen, the people said, asking no=
t to be identified discussing information that=E2=80=99s not yet public.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That includes GreenSky, the installment-lendin=
g firm it bought last year, along with its credit-card ventures and transac=
tion banking, which handles corporate deposits and was previously part of t=
he investment-banking group.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So Goldman will have <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29401395.284514/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9=
hcnRpY2xlcy9nb2xkbWFuLXBsYW5zLXN3ZWVwaW5nLXJlb3JnYW5pemF0aW9uLWNvbWJpbmluZy=
1pbnZlc3RtZW50LWJhbmtpbmctYW5kLXRyYWRpbmctMTE2NjU5NzMzNjg_bW9kPWhwX2xlYWRfc=
G9zMw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7625d259" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> three divisions</a>, ro=
ughly transaction banking, money management, and the investment bank. I don=
=E2=80=99t know how much that matters:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The changes to the banking and tra=
ding business are expected to be minimal, with the remaining slate of leade=
rs taking over the reins of the new, combined group. The combination is dri=
ven partly by a shift to showcase to investors the relative strength of tha=
t business compared with peers across Wall Street.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it seems culturally significant. For its e=
ntire history until this week, Goldman=C2=A0<em>was=C2=A0</em>an investment=
 bank. Now it is=C2=A0a big financial company that=C2=A0<em>has=C2=A0</em>a=
n investment bank.</p>
