width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;"> talked on Thursday</a> about two somewhat contradictor=
y visions of anti-ESG:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">One vision is that states=C2=A0should=
 reject ESG and try only=C2=A0to maximize their financial returns, without =
worrying about social or political factors.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">The other vision is that Republican-run states should reject ESG =
because =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D tends to involve left-wing priorities, and Re=
publican-run states should instead pursue right-wing priorities with their =
investments.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Most people=C2=A0in the anti-ESG movement will=
=C2=A0<em>tell=C2=A0</em>you that it is just about maximizing financial ret=
urns and avoiding politics. But then you get a case like this where the sch=
ool district simply incinerates some money to pursue=C2=A0Republican politi=
cal goals! But they had the nerve to ask the bank for the money back.</p>
