om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">SPACs</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I feel like people do not understand the basic=
 economic proposition=C2=A0of a special purpose acquisition company? <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29401395.284514/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMjAvbW9yZ2FuLXN=
0YW5sZXktbG9zdC1zb21lLWhhcmQtZHJpdmVzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEwMTcyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJn=
V0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTAxNyZ1d=
G1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4233a018" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  A SPAC is a gamble by its sponsors</a>. The sponsors put in some money =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0let=E2=80=99s say it=E2=80=99s $8 million =E2=80=94=C2=A0to =
pay startup costs to raise a pool of cash from public investors. Then they =
have about two years to look for a private company to merge with and take p=
ublic. If they find a target, negotiate a merger, get approval from the pub=
lic investors, and take it public, then they make a lot of money. Let=E2=80=
=99s say they make $54 million, or roughly seven times what they put in. Go=
od payoff. If they fail to find a target, or they can=E2=80=99t negotiate t=
he deal, or if the public investors don=E2=80=99t approve of the deal, then=
 they lose their $8 million.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile the public investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
the people who put money into the pool of cash =E2=80=94=C2=A0get back (1) =
shares of the target company, if the SPAC succeeds, or (2) the money they p=
ut in, with a little bit of interest, if it fails. In Case 2, the public in=
vestors basically break even; the interest they got from the=C2=A0SPAC isn=
=E2=80=99t materially worse than they would have gotten in a bank account. =
In Case 1, the public investors get shares in a newly public company, which=
 is good if the company is good or bad if the company is bad. So you could =
separate the public investors=E2=80=99 result into Case 1a, =E2=80=9Cshares=
 that go up,=E2=80=9D and Case 1b, =E2=80=9Cshares that go down.=E2=80=9D I=
n Case 1a, you=E2=80=99re happy; getting valuable shares is better than get=
ting your money back. In Case 1b, you=E2=80=99re sad, and you would rather =
have gotten your money back.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But all that stuff is virtually irrelevant for=
 the SPAC=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>sponsors</em>. The sponsors lose $8 million in=
 Case 2: The public investors break even, but the sponsors lose their inves=
tment. And the sponsors get $54 million in Case 1 =E2=80=94=C2=A01a or 1b, =
doesn=E2=80=99t matter =E2=80=94=C2=A0because for=C2=A0<em>them</em>, all t=
hat matters is doing the deal. If they do a deal, they get $54 million; if =
they don=E2=80=99t, they lose $8 million.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is not=C2=A0<em>quite=C2=A0</em>right; th=
ere are features that align the interests of the SPAC=E2=80=99s sponsors wi=
th the public investors more than what I have suggested here. The big one i=
s that the sponsors do not literally get a check for $54 million: They get =
(roughly $54 million worth of) shares in the target company, and the more v=
aluable that ends up being the better they do. (There are also various sort=
s of lockups, clawbacks, etc., to make the sponsors=E2=80=99 success more c=
ontingent on the company=E2=80=99s success. Also, the public investors get =
to vote on the deal, and presumably they=E2=80=99ll vote no on bad deals.) =
But even if the target company does=C2=A0<em>terribly</em>, the sponsors ge=
t so many shares that they make a huge profit,=C2=A0<em>as long as they act=
ually do the deal</em>.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29401395.284514/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS=
9hcnRpY2xlcy9zcGFjLXNwb25zb3JzLXdlcmUtd2lubmVycy1ldmVuLW9uLWxvc2Vycy0xMTY2N=
Tc5NDUxOA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1b3e2782" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> a Wall Street Journal=
 article</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As the air has come out of the SPAC boom of re=
cent years, a clear winner has emerged: the money managers who oversaw the =
blank-check companies and who kept making profits even in the face of signi=
ficant losses to stock investors.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Stock-market investors in SPACs that merged wi=
th private companies since 2015 lost an average 37% of their investment a y=
ear after the merger through the end of September, according to the authors=
 of a forthcoming paper on SPACs in the Review of Financial Studies, an aca=
demic journal.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At the same time, SPAC managers, known as spon=
sors, turned an average investment of about $8 million into about $54 milli=
on, giving them average annualized returns of 110% on their initial investm=
ent in the SPACs, the authors found.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes look this is right as far as it goes, but =
it looks only at a subset of SPACs, the subset of =E2=80=9CSPACs that merge=
d with private companies.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s like saying that people w=
ho bought winning lottery tickets, on average, made money. If you ran a SPA=
C that succeeded =E2=80=94=C2=A0by the narrow SPAC standard of =E2=80=9Cdid=
 a merger=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0then you turned $8 million into $54 milli=
on, even though the public investors lost money. But if you ran a SPAC that=
 failed =E2=80=94=C2=A0that didn=E2=80=99t find a merger =E2=80=94=C2=A0the=
n you turned $8 million into zero, while your public investors got their mo=
ney back with interest.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously the point here is that success for t=
he public investors is the opposite: You=E2=80=99d rather get your money ba=
ck than lose 37% of your investment. On average, sponsors do better from th=
e SPACs that succeed, but regular investors do better from the ones that fa=
il.</p>
